---
title: "How to Build a Technology Roadmap Around Business Outcomes, Not Feature Lists"
date: "2024-12-03"
summary: "Build a technology roadmap around business outcomes. Features are the means. Outcomes are the end."
coverImage: ""
tags:
  - "Business Strategy"
author: "Redevise"
---

Your technology roadmap has 47 features. The features are prioritized. The business outcomes are not. The roadmap is a feature list. Not a strategy.

A technology roadmap built around business outcomes starts with the outcome. Not the feature. The outcome is "reduce customer churn by 15 percent." The features are the means to that outcome.

Implementing this structure effectively requires a systematic, three-step methodology:

Define the outcomes. What should the business achieve in the next 12 months. Reduce churn. Increase revenue. Improve retention. The outcomes are specific.

Identify the capabilities required. What capabilities does the business need to achieve the outcomes. Better customer data. Faster response times. Proactive outreach.

Identify the features that build those capabilities. The features are the means. Not the end.

In our client engagements at Redevise, we regularly design and deploy these solutions. For example, when partnering with a fast-growing team in 2025, we built a technology roadmap. The old roadmap had 30 features. The new roadmap had 8 outcomes. The outcomes were specific. The features were aligned. The roadmap was achievable. The old roadmap was not.

The teams that build feature lists are the ones with busy teams and unclear progress. The teams that build outcome roadmaps are the teams with focused teams and clear progress.

Define the outcomes. Identify the capabilities. Identify the features. The roadmap serves the business.
